If you listen, above all, to the music as a background and you will only listen to it every day for a while, as in the tram, then you are enough with any mobile that you play.
This is what virtually any mobile phone can do.
You should not even be interested in the format in which the mobile or player plays the music.
The MP3 is played by everyone and practically all the music that comes to it will be in this format.
It is among the most widespread and except for it the absolute majority of the devices play music in WMA format.
Less include the AAC format (format used by Apple and its iPod).
The best mobile phones also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
It is enough through the mobile internet to visit the competent pages of the operator (or any other service provider) and buy a song or an album.
This service alone could be a weighty argument for acquiring a mobile for music.
Unfortunately the offer of the operators is miserable and most are limited only to the themes of fleeting success of the radios.
The prices are also not the lowest.
However, in general, it is assumed that precisely this way of selling music (whether by GSM, internet or wireless internet) in the future will dominate the music industry.
Most people always carry a mobile phone.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you will find the phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player will be forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least handsfree ones.
If not, you can use an integrated player that has virtually every mobile even if it is at least an MP3 player.
Probably the biggest advantage for many mobile phones with music will be their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000.
