Again, the advantage of players is nothing but their easy service.
The simplest players - by no means necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - are actually handled by anyone.
The minimal functions, its handling similar to the previous current cassettes or also to the record players is evident.
It does not represent a threat in the sense that by mistake we connect to the internet with the mobile and, consequently, gigantic count by downloading data.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g., the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for changing the memory card (M2 type, micro SD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of a suitable card you will reach two thousand crowns.
However, be careful.
The basic models are usually equipped with only a 2 GB maximum capacity card.
Only the most expensive ones have a memory of 8 GB.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a look at Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (maximum 2 GB) it is not necessary to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If considered among the most discerning music lovers, take advantage of the more specialized mobile-walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have separate keys for the MP3 which makes a service as comfortable as that of the same player.
The most specialized of all is Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles of the line walkman have almost identical use as that of a standalone MP3 player.
The same service and the same category in terms of price, over four thousand crowns, but with a greater memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and accumulator capacity (usually 15 hours, with a maximum performance of up to 35 hours), the brand mentioned more arria brings them MP3 players.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not gonna take long to get there.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written on mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the whole Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of the regulation of roaming rates will probably come to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators the SMS they send from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacking competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical, because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to lament that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, has already said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a significant fall in prices to which the classic operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for this type of trader and that they can succeed.
There is no need to look too far for examples.
In February of this year we inform you about the debut of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator managed to get more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, behind Mobilking is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order for them to function effectively, they have far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry with them relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, this type of virtual operators usually profile themselves with low expenses - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that however, is often countered by the offer of more tight services.
So, for example, Tesco mobile in Great Britain offers SMS at least half cheaper than the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows can be a good hit also the bet on a nothing trivial goal group.
This operator is specifically aimed at the man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - it's the operator he likes and he can be trusted," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which works this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept as Poland could engage in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
Also from the point of view of the offer of services is relatively saturated"
There are no chances in the Czech Republic, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be any virtual operator in the Czech Republic that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, it’s about launching Mobilking in other countries in our region,” Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, spokeswoman for financial group Penta, said in a telephone conversation for mobil.cz.
Indirectly he said that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything possible so that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, in order to be able to offer our customers not only fixed phone services but also mobile phone services.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have made progress in the meetings,” said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So, maybe they flash better times.
It seems that, for unofficial information, the first official operator would have to arrive possibly by the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment we believe that the situation is ideal for the appearance of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this field,” said Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, spokesperson for Telefónica O2.
Other operators refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional conformity with O2's opinion, adds: "To date we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to develop."
“In the T-Mobile network, it will be difficult to find any virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have on the table some concrete contract that it was possible to study in such a short horizon.
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of cost sharing and infrastructure.
We consider it to be the biggest contribution from a customer’s point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for fast mobile internet."
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition, which would lead to a drop in prices and thus a drop in profits.
So why make it easier to enter the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull the same string, proof of this is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the biggest pressure on <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was at the time of the entry of U:fon by T-Mobile.
This is attested by the public information accessible on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds: “In addition, it was not long ago that the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was opened up to a fourth operator.
As far as the character of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is concerned, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would entail great requirements for him and, above all, for his services."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just the position of the <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (UOHS).
However, it expressed its typical stance on this issue.
The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator was concluded.
So far no agreement has been concluded as the offer from potential interested parties was rather not interesting enough for the classic operators," Kristián Chalupa, from the Department of Foreign Relations of the UOHS, added to our question.
These statements are not surprising to the representatives of the operators.
For offices that must represent the interests of consumers it is more than a consideration, apart from that they must note that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual operators operate normally, we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the lower prices of mobile phone services"
Obviously, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market means and the fall in prices are not in the interest of UOHS.
The really dramatic shock in this whole case is in the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it is really a coincidence, is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard fight for competition.
"The Office in this regard has found no signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore, they do not have a corresponding increase in accountability in their actions on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are lacking, as are telecommunications regulators,” Chalupa added.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of conflict.
Evidently, there is an analysis of relevant markets by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of commercial tendering.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another view - for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile operator - with all its logic - has the monopoly of its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument were not accepted, at least for UOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators rise strikingly similarly.
The current complaints of the interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators they collide with many similar impediments.
Carrying responsibility on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which the UOHS washes its hands in all this matter.
We have already met him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law was recently introduced to expand <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>’s competition in the field of commercial tenders, which was not implemented, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This must be well known by the representatives of UOHS, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
All is well, when no one looks
At the same time, something like a pseudo-virtual operator still works unnoticed, which in the Czech mobile networks already exist a few.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile phone services that, however, only a part are public.
These are usually companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a few of these companies get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the carrier, acts as a classic business customer of the same ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that business conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If cases such as those cited were discovered, one could speak of infringement in the terms of the contract that could translate into the end of the collaboration with the given company," Martina Kemrová replied to the question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity carried out by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
In the case of the three mentioned companies, it can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators is against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they make no negligible profits and, at the same time - unlike authentic virtual operators - they in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns us of the possible problems: "the law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
They must also accept that their phone’s SIM card is not in their name so they cannot dispose of it at all as a normal carrier customer.”
Precisely this is what should seem to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> minimally strange.
There is also a new question for the UOHS.
If mobile operators turn their eyes in this type of procedure, why do they block the virtual operator’s entry?
It is necessary to add that the UOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want it should not be content with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this story and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As was already clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant drop in the prices of services.
At the same time, in practically every country where the virtual operator emerged, the classic operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this irruption.
The arguments used by these were practically all identical - too small, a market, eventually, too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, at the moment the regulatory bodies have intervened and in none of the cases defended the operators but their customers.
Whether it was with formal measures or informal pressure, the first virtual operator emerged and with it others began to emerge.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body all this case happens as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot help but be impressed that the confusion of the attributions in these cases suits them.
But let's not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator actually arrives in these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market is likely to start moving again.
If one of the operators allows a virtual mobile operator to enter, it will be difficult for the UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
