Rats also have feelings.
It is said that a rat or a cockroach feeling danger flees, why is it also afraid?
Joseph Le Doux, the scientist in the field of neurology, is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
How can we control whether they, behaving in the same way as we do, feel the same way?
In an internet magazine called "Edge" the contributions of famous scientists have been published for many years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series the chosen answers to the question What do you think is true without being able to prove it?
I think animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it so far, although we can’t even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case we can at least expect it because all human brains have the same fundamental configuration.
But as soon as we devote ourselves to other species and include questions about sensation and consciousness in general, we enter the unknown realm because the hardware doesn’t match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same as the other animals: it makes itself dead, flees or attacks.
People behave in a similar way, from which some scientists make conclusions about comparable subjective experience.
Naturally I don't think so.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to infect our subjective experience with that of animals.
First, they almost always include the circuits associated by human consciousness of the lateral prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex (because of their involvement in short memory and executive functions that direct behavior).
This broad part is much more developed in the case of humans than that of other primates and seems to be absolutely lacking in other creatures.
Considering at least the aspects related to our consciousness that depends on the prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex, including knowledge about who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is a reason to assume that even man differs from the other primates.
