Eatonville, the first fully black-inhabited city incorporated in the country and Zora Neale Hurston’s childhood home, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: “the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 men of color, 300 good swimmers, many guavas, two schools and not a prison.”
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Fair in Eatonville to pay tribute to Mrs. Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, in many ways, the city she described – making it also a tourist stage by including it in the Florida travel guide produced by the Depression Season Federal Writers Project – remains a separate place.
The city remains independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Mrs. Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their true ideas with the white man, who “knows so little about us and doesn’t know what is missing.”
Even now, in the year that a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, has drawn attention to start a dialogue on the issue of race, many remain cautious in front of the outsider.
“We are very cautious about the way our story is told,” said Jones Hortense, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city’s oldest church.
"It has to be right."
Eatonville has always been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is at the same time a historical model of the affirmation of blacks and a community of almost 2,400 people living under a level of poverty double the national average.
It is a literary center, but also a repaired example of the rural culture of the Black South - sometimes scorned, sometimes praised - that was born from slavery in America.
No wonder, if those who live here are both proud and reserved.
And the preoccupation with Eatonville's image really started with Zora, as no one here calls her Mrs. Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world through her deep dialect books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs in the Florida Guide transformed the city, just off Route 17, a road that runs through central Florida often forgotten inwards the history of blacks and human drama.
Having a cement face in both life and literature, Ms. Hurston took her readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then in more private areas.
"Out of the road on the left," he wrote, "there is the modern brown public school with its white finishes, its well-maintained gardens and playgrounds, cared for by Howard Miller, as he can barely read and write."
She also mentions the widow's new husband Dash and writes that Glenn Lee "sells drinks of all kinds and anything goes with transitory rooms."
Thus, in just a few hundred words, Ms. Hurston relates Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Obviously, this Fodor did not.
In fact, not everyone appreciated the portrait.
"Zora described it as it was," said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the Johnson girls who Hurston immortalized by quoting men singing colorless songs about her beauty.
He added, “Some people didn’t like that.”
Ms. Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who returned frequently after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Franklin Augusto, 77, remembers that when Ms. Hurston arrived in town, she did so without warning in a large Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still prides itself on dressing with dignity.
Most residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin said, while many laughed sarcasticly.
“People were always very happy to see Zora,” Mr. Franklin continues.
But, she adds, swinging in her chair in a backyard overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Ms. Hurston was probably baptized, "she never stayed too long."
When Ms. Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were no longer in print.
Like most of the world, Eatonville also seemed to have forgotten about her.
Although she was a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only woman of color at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous tomb in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had been living.
In Eatonville, there were no major commemorative ceremonies, no major public readings.
“I don’t think her contribution to the world or her heritage was understood,” said Valerie Boyd, author of “Wrapped in Rainbows,” a biography of Ms. Hurston published in 2003.
A certain turn came in the ’80s.
Orange County officials wanted to put a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the two-lane main street of the labor community.
Expansion of the Orlando area had already pushed Interstate 4 across the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to it relatively idyllic isolation from the community.
In the 1950s, the struggle for racial mixing brought hatred closer to the community.
