"I capture the master off-stage to extract his character" Günther Bauer_Photographer
No heels, no ruffles, no premiere suits.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of concentration in interpretation to obtain the relaxed appearance of man or woman.
Aside from the artist.
The other, the person.
Inseparable except in the intimacy, in those moments alien to the public, when finding the privacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen look or the expressiveness of some hands, carefree because they are not going to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer alternates in "Flamenco-people" the theatricality of some stagings with singers, dancers and guitarists with that lesser-known side of these masters.
With this proposal, the photographer collects the particular iconography of flamenco from different areas.
Included in the program of the Flemish Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, increasing every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco-people" "can be any people but, seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists on the stage.
These people portrayed "on the street" are artists capable of transmitting on stage passion, sadness, joy... captivating the public.
To capture the personality of these artists you do not have to take pictures of the stage.
They carry their personality and character inside.
What I was interested in was creating an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture with the camera the personality of the greats of flamenco.
With the taste of the "Sing of the Mines" festival, Bauer began in 1978 a long journey to portray the singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
They are portraits that, due to the selection of the camera and the material, recall classical photography.
The application of different stylistic means breaks with the classical basis of the image, giving it modernity, an idea that reflects how Bauer himself understands flamenco: "A music with very traditional roots, which evolves and surprises every day".
It is not the action of the dance, the singing or the touch itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, that captivates the public with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential, with the goblin that becomes visible in a way of feeling, being and being are and have been the constant of this work that is presented these days in the gallery El Photomata.
Known flamenco figures such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, configure this selection of almost seventy artists photographed.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited in the exhibition.
Bauer’s passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with “Portraits of Veteran Athletes” (“SportARTproject”).
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco-people", the photographer admits that "I love portraying people, meeting them and being able to enter a moment in their life, whether a long or short moment.
I think portraiture is the most difficult genre in photography.
You meet or confront people, characters, who sometimes you don’t know, or who leave you only a few minutes to take the photo.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas a reality.”
