Talking asleep
Some kids talk at night.
I do not mean those who wake up very quietly telling us something that happened the previous day, but children who talk while asleep.
The first time it happens, you may be scared, but it doesn’t really matter.
It is a benign sleep disturbance called somnilochies.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one has been told he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once in meseS...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, bedwetting or sleepwalking, but it doesn’t have to be.
As we have already mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fever, stressful situations or overexcitement.
It is an under-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
He may speak in a calm tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or the opposite (screaming, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him a way out.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, so it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress disorder).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are scary or a little violent.
With children who are very nervous and have a hard time relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will help the child have a quieter sleep.
Once the somnylochies appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything of what has happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
Even though he's talking, he's asleep and so he's resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed during several episodes it would be advisable to consult or find out what is causing so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common), do not fall into the temptation of interrogating him in order to extract information from him.
You will get nothing, because when you are asleep you are not conscious enough to organize your thinking.
Also you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say that, so very careful in how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can question him at night to know his secrets.
Not even kidding.
That generates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don’t worry, it’s not a bad thing, it’s an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
