The interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec was celebrating its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, had reason to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it regained public confidence that had been seriously hesitant by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this drama and the discontent of the public, the Government of Canada conducted a public survey in February 1994, presided over by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations that such a disaster should not be repeated any more.
While Judge Krever was slow to present his relationship, certain provinces then created a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mission.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, almost 38 per cent of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Having made a lot of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work during the years that followed, we have regained public confidence,” he says before proudly asserting that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that "confidence is something extremely fragile " .
Since its inception on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we were witnessing in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
Then we rely on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know it and when a serious disease can emanate from it, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we introduce exclusionary measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been proven beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
This episode showed us so that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique for HIV detection appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests that allow to detect directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
Nucleic acid tests allowed to shorten the period between the time the person has been infected and the time the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period by less than a week.
This substantially reduces the risk that certain donors will become infected without knowing it and that we will not be able to detect them.
These improvements significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS from a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
“That means 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I think that today you can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without worries," says the head of the management of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant," says Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for a sufficient supply.
" Needs are increasing as the population ages.
As the most aggressive anti-carcinogenic treatments, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which regroups on average only 3 per cent of Quebecers eligible for blood donation. "
All persons in good health, 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria can nevertheless donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of the people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they traveled in a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
The hardships are very rare.
But members of this donor network need to be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to be a regular donor.
Since today’s life is very rampant, we rarely find the time to spend an hour donating her blood,” Francine Décary says.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood of stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
"We have celebrated a few weeks ago, the placing on the bench of our thousandth sample of umbilical cord blood and it is expected to take more than a thousand of these per year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts early next year,” says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
" Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot enjoy this," since Héma-Québec does not have the resources to propose this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
