Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, vice president and director of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Following Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold claims that the largest gold company in the world tried a €6 million defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small publishing house in order to provoke a “transparent public debate.”
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of persecution for defamation, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely concealed by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to harm anyone who dares to take a position contrary to his own?
The outcome of the lawsuit is of little importance, the authors and publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defense and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers held by the almost bottomless pockets of the miner.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly arrangement that will muzzle the opposition as well as scare anyone who will dare to re-examine the question.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is in front of public opinion that he would have had to present his view of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually done for the change of ideas and not for punches.
It was therefore enough for the mining company to open its books, its records and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have clarified the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects the petitions and letters of support for the authors of Noir Canada.
Could Mr. Garver possibly explain how he can call for a "public" debate by scorning its views?
According to the vice president, this word appears to refer only to highly paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In democracy, detractors also have the right to speak.
What he doesn’t understand – or what he doesn’t want to understand – Barrick Gold, is that the public holding the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does so mostly because it rejects the brutal manner of the miner.
This audience is willing to listen to Barrick and judge him, but based on civilized changes in arguments, and not within the framework of what many people perceive as a chase-bite (in pursuing the "public debate ", Barrick Gold has just filed a request with respect to the authors of Noir Canada urging them to no longer use this word).
In addition to Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, the Barrick Gold process is a direct attack on the freedom of university search and truth, essential for all democratic societies.
