If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that displease the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, under the penalty of many persecutions, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, he could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have a right of reply.
The university world, to which we belong, has long managed debates and disagreements and resolved conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate persecution clearly shows that, contrary to what he intends, he has no desire to make a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, but also for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place devices that limit this kind of abusive persecution.
