Psychology of Overlaps: Why Do We Spend More Money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at New York University discovered the neurological-economic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in the journal Science, people do not want to lose in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
The scientists attempted to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played lottery, the other participated in an auction and meanwhile the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment were examined using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) system.
In both games participants could earn money, but during auctions, where it is fundamental to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the functioning of the complex called stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "self-premium" mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention so as not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To support their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment, three groups bet against one person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply told the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group was promised that if they won, they would receive an additional $15 in prize money.
On the other hand, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction the members of the group even lost that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, checking the hypothesis of the neurologists, members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than members of the control group and the "winner" group.
“These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
Until now, they explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped to resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: When should you go to the doctor?
Around 500 million people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of people infected in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand receive treatment because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the common name for different diseases of the liver caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis viruses depending on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: hepatitis A and E via food (e.g. with water or food contagious), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body moods (sperm, vaginal mood, saliva).
It is advisable for travelers to protect themselves by vaccine against virus A and B, against C there are no vaccines.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, it manifests itself through a poor general state, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that appear on the skin and in the white of the eyes jaundice, excrement becomes clear, urine dark and healing can last even two - three weeks.
Every year, one million people die worldwide from cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to calculations, only one in ten infected receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can lead to liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most people who are infected do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms appear only 20-30 years later.
Therefore, early recognition, systematic medical control, is very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and those who wear tattoos.
There are currently about 200 million people in the world who suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with routine laboratory control as well, it is worth consulting your family doctor when experiencing any unknown symptoms.
The disease has a cure if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so you can suppress the infection and prevent cancer.
30 September is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their early recognition.
