You're what you say about yourself
On its tenth birthday, Google can say: you can find it both in people’s pockets, as well as in the sky above their heads; it knows where they spent their holidays, which doctors they visit and what they are interested in.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's executives, this is still not enough.
On the other hand, skeptics who draw a parallel with the Orwelian vision do not see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main goal is to gather as much personal data about its users as possible, and this is necessary to be able to fulfill the original goals of the founders of Google: “Let’s gather all the information in the world in one system!”
According to the leader of Google, the company even after ten years of work that stirred the world is still in the initial phase of the effort to be able to handle all the information.
To the question what is going to happen in five years, Schmidt replied: I wish Google could answer questions such as "What to do tomorrow?" or "What would be the job that would suit me best?" - however, the software will not be able to answer questions that seem so simple as long as there is not enough information from users.
Not all Internet users are aware that while browsing the Internet, the searched keywords, IP addresses and pages that they went to at the end of the search are accurately stored.
Thanks for example to Personalized Search that debuted two years ago, users can store their own browsing history, they can revisit what they were looking for before, what they opened and thanks to this history will generate much more personalized searches - on this same logic will be based the Recommendations, on which the system will offer us products and services based on the preferences previously defined and stored.
What will happen if they take advantage of my data against myself, if they collect information about my activities? - ask those users who are concerned about seeing the information monopoly of Google.
In most cases rather the potential represented by the company is what can be fearful and not remorse, fear of punishment, yearning for freedom or rebellion against power.
However, it is a confirmed fact that they not only preserve, but in justifiable cases also give to third parties all the expressions sought, in these cases there is nothing that protects the personal rights of internet users.
Perhaps the most debated example of recent times was the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, when Google handed over to the Brazilian government the information on its website, called Orkut, to identify the pedophiles.
On the other hand, internet users who care about people’s rights, in May were relieved when the company, along with the EFF, successfully proved in court that it was right in its litigation with the FBI: according to the ruling, Google, through any of the points of the constitution, cannot be compelled to provide any information requested by the FBI secretly.
(At the same time, the federal government managed to get under the pretext of reinforcing the child protection law passed years ago, nearly fifty thousand Web addresses and about a thousand searched phrases, but without obtaining the search lists of individual users, nor the complete lists of Web pages and keywords of the last two months.)
This is a rather contradictory view of Google: it is criticized by those who are afraid of providing their personal data because they think it harms their privacy, their private life by starting to use Google services, and they rebel against it as against multinational conservative image companies.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its enthusiastic followers, netizens and users from other countries, see in them the future generation, the "avant-garde corporation", not their rival, Microsoft, cataloged by its Windows as conqueror of the world, no matter how much they both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, nor money for their applications, the code is open and the free program package, constantly updated and seems more youthful, more collaborating than the practice of the official software giant.
But it may also be because geeks accurately see the very problematic relationship between people’s rights and the Internet that was produced precisely by one of the most mentioned keywords in recent years: the Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about collaboration, leaving intentional footprints behind us and taking advantage of the available communication channels, and while the measures of these vary individually, the essence remains the same: to show ourselves.
A normal young person can have a profile on numerous collective pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and can even link them with other services, such as Twitter or last.fm that offers a list of their music habits, then these can be included in a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, can also have a blog, in which the most recent photo galleries that are stored in the Flickr automatically appear.
We may know numerous cases from which it follows that for example the bride, upon seeing the stream of photographs of the next morning of common friends, learns who spent the night before her fraudulent boyfriend or can fire the employee of a company because he writes his sincere opinion on the direction of the company: one thing is for sure, the definition of private life was completely revalued.
A person’s “on-line” life is what he shows of himself – this is the definition that hides behind the behavior of the youth of our day.
And anyone who wants to hide something, or at least seeks to dodge Google’s monopoly, can do so (starting with Scroogle, for example, which uses Google’s search system, but leaves no footprints).
There are many people who do not want to register on collective pages to prevent them from being able to find them, but you can replace Google's "online" applications, from text-writing software to image and news-reading applications with alternative versions that do not connect with gigantic servers or prepare the most perfect profile possible about us.
Public opinion expects almost openly the day Google shows its true face.
The company with its current value of $156 billion is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising surfaces threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, while the services that are increasingly rapidly introduced cause serious headaches not only to Microsoft but also to Microsoft.
Critical observers, however, will find the contradictions alarming as well: for example, the top management flatly rejected employee protest after doubling the price of the company’s childcare, considered the unlimited number of employees’ food interests to be too expensive, but all this is nothing compared to the fact that in 2006 the Chinese regime violated morale under pressure from the Chinese government and the company and filtered them according to the agreement.
One of the company's internal regulations says that they will not announce any new services in advance, but only when it was ready to work, which if it is certain is that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years will be able to turn the world upside down: while some believe that our own scanning and archiving project of Google's previous books and journals will acquire such dimensions that the company will soon be cited by the Supreme Court of the United States, and others fear it.
And the fact that Google is going to create a genetic database, will be able to provide a good raw material for writers of science fiction works, the Scroogled, novel by popular Cory Doctorow, describes in Orwelian form that future, in which a man only of the Google data can be described alarmingly well.
