Smart car mimics bumblebee flight
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of existing obstacle sensors in nature?
For example, the bumblebees.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, bumblebees provided the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the robotic steering system of type BR23C cars imitating nature, which was given the characteristics of bumblebees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can dodge all collisions.
During the flight each bumblebee creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our security protective capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technological director of PR and development and research.
Composite eyes of bumblebees that are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees play an important role.
To copy the function of composite eyes, engineers used the laser length measurement system.
It identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at a 180-degree angle, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the microprocessor of the vehicle that is immediately transformed into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle imitating the movements of the bumblebees, modifies the direction by turning the wheels as necessary.
Unlike any existing system, this maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"If it were not, the vehicle robot would not be able to react quickly enough to dodge obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety capsule, in a layer within which all kinds of collisions are currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process should reflect what a bumblebee does to dodge other bumblebees.
This process must be done in the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonal, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bumblebees to dodge other bumblebees, here they only used as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotational movement and the acceleration in addition to the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have higher energy density, which means they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the processing capacity of the data, let alone the storage capacity.
This apparatus in every second should only process a few input signals and react as the case may be.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
There is no need for gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately dodge obstacles, which according to calculations of the Nissan, within ten years will be incorporated into the models manufactured in series.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding existing obstacles in his way.
