The written version of the $700 billion bailout package law has been prepared to be applied in several phases to buy bad credit from banks.
In the first phase, half of the money will be spent.
According to East Coast schedule during new consultations that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, congressional leaders reached an agreement on the $700 billion bailout package in total, after several days of discussion, Reuters reported.
“We have made significant progress,” said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic president of the U.S. Congress, saying the agreement needs only to be formalized in a document.
The commitment to the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the Minister of Finance, speaking about the outcome of the compromise said: this program will work and be efficient but more action is needed. According to Pelosi, it is not about saving Wall Street, but about turning the economy around.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of the Asian markets, i.e. on Sunday before 8 p.m., according to Washington time (i.e. before 2 p.m., according to Central European time), without causing a spectacular jump in the exchanges.
On the bill called the Emergency Law for Economic Stabilization of 2008, the U.S. Congress will vote first on Monday and then the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelosi and then the White House also celebrated the news about the deal.
"We are pleased with the progress made overnight and highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
The program is different from the Bush administration’s original proposal to spend all of the $700 billion to buy poor-quality credit-fund securities.
Now only half of the $700 billion can be spent, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, of this sum the Ministry of Finance will buy bonds of credit, underrated securities and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president's decision.
This program will be controlled by a special body, in which the president of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion could be spent after a new Congressional decision.
According to the law, the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it can simultaneously buy bad credits, mortgages and securities of credit fund, in addition to other "poisonous" type credits as well.
The purchase can be made at auction or directly - informed competent people of the ministry.
The law allows affected companies to participate in an insurance program where the finance portfolio guarantees the worrying elements, for which the companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson said: “The law ensures the necessary financial means, which can even reach $700 billion to meet the urgent needs of the American financial system, whether it is the purchase of bad financial means, their insurance or the prevention of risks that could cause the collapse of some large financial institutions.
We do everything necessary to be ready to introduce the law as soon as they sign it.
On the other hand, the heads of the banks who are in distress and are waiting for the help of the state will be able to count on the official limitation of their indemnities, which the American slang simply calls parachutes of gold.
Payments will only be limited in certain cases, and the limitations will depend on the form of assistance provided by the Ministry of Finance.
The limitation means that if the ministry buys in the framework of an auction, an extra tax will be imposed for the gold parachutes, unless the bank’s failed boss retires.
By buying bad credits directly, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the compensation of the bosses is not overstated.
In addition to the above, the existing gold parachute contracts will not be changed, the limitations relate only to new contracts to stimulate participation in the programme.
This is the first case in American history that will be in effect a legal limitation on the revenues of CEOs, said Democrat Barney Frank, chairman of the congressional commission responsible for financial services.
The State will also have the right to acquire shares of the banks participating in the program, thus reducing the risk of the taxpayers, since in the end they can even make profits from the transaction as soon as the economy and with it the bank recovers.
According to the bill in the next five years, the president will have to present to Congress a proposal on how to repay the financial sector’s losses to taxpayers.
Of course, on both sides there were those who expressed their reservations regarding the project.
This is not what the American citizens entrusted to us, that is, taxpayer dollars are not being protected,” said California Republican Congressman Darrell Issa.
Ohio Democrat colleague Mary Kaptur said the measures urged the same ones responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial selling prices rose 0.1 percent compared to last month's prices and 12.9 percent compared to August 2007's prices - the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose 1.1 percent from July 2008 and decreased 3.9 percent from the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices rose 0.7 percent from the previous month and 3.2 percent from the previous year.
Industrial selling prices rose only to a minimum, at 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry sectors rose minimally, down 0.1 percent from July.
The largest increase in the magnitude of prices occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 percent), primarily due to a 4.6 percent increase in bags and belts per month and a 2.5 percent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in prices in the chemical materials production branch (1.6 percent).
There was a price decrease in the petrochemical sector (1.4 percent), in the production of electric machines and instruments (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 percent).
The prices of papermaking, publishers and printing presses did not change.
In the other sectors of the processing industry, prices increased between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water, which represent an important weight within domestic trade, there was an increase of 0.3 percent in August, first of all as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from the 1st of July.
In a twelve-month comparison – in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors – the biggest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metal processing sector, an increase of 13.2 percent was observed, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, which was of decisive importance, there was an increase of 11 percent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 percent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 percent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the pace of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
During the past year in the processing industry globally prices increased by 10.2 percent.
Electricity, gas, heat and water prices surpassed the previous year’s prices by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly increase in prices (0.7 percent) was recorded in the sectors of investment goods.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 percent, with prices in the energy sector and intermediate sectors not changing from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared with the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and the intermediary industry (16.8 percent).
In consumer goods-producing industries, there was a decrease of 6.8 percent and in investment goods of 1.4 percent.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 percent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a 3.9 percent decrease.
The price of our national currency in one month fell by 1.7 percent against the euro and by 7.1 percent against the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
