MP3 readers accused of putting hearing at risk
Listening to high-volume music for a long period of time using portable musical devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing injuries.
This is what the European Commission says, which in a statement released on Brussels cites the opinion of the Scientific Commission on the emerging and recently identified health risk (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
"From this scientific opinion - it is read in the note - it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable musical devices weekly for more than an hour a day having the device at high volume risk a permanent loss of hearing ability."
“I am concerned that such a high number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and high-sounding cell phones can unconsciously ruin their ears in an irremediable way,” says Meglena Kuneva.
"From the scientific evidence - the responsibility Ue follows - a clear risk emerges and we must react quickly.
What counts is raising consumer awareness and making this information publicly available.
We must also re-examine the existing control systems in the light of this scientific opinion, so that they are broadly effective and have the pace with the new technology."
Bruxel had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, seeing the widespread use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise that it causes.
"Scientists - the executive Ue concludes - confirm that it is of concern and the European Commission will now examine together with member states and stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and related devices."
Currently, there is already a European safety standard limiting the noise level of portable musical devices to 100 dB, but concern increases as the hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to greatly limit this damage by resorting to solutions such as reducing levels and the time of exposure to noise.
In its opinion, the Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical devices listen to music at high volume (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours a week exceed the current limit for maximum noise in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods, risk a permanent loss of hearing after a period of 5 years.
It means that it affects 5-10% of users of such devices and the number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
