Farewell to the old Paradiso cinema, cities cancel the historic rooms
The historic cinemas close favoring the Multiplexes.
“A city without cinemas in a blind city is like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the major Italian urban centers and also in the provincial cities.
The process of marginalization of the cinemas, which with the birth of the great methions in the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono salas in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear are almost always historical places, full of memory, "is as if a friend died, a acquaintance with whom a piece of place and so much emotion was shared", observes the director of the new cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won the cousin Oscar and the grand prize of the jury to Cannes, which told the poetry of a provincial cinema and the nostalgia for the way to live the lost cinema.
The figures given by the ANEC, the main association of traders, are clear: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and to pay most are mostly the halls of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are first, Emilia-Romagna with 82 fewer cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the person responsible for its disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, these three Italian regions are own that have registered the largest number of new meticone cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
“The Italian exercise has developed irrationally,” observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, “it would be useful if new structures were to be built, but it would be necessary to ensure the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all of its frequenters are willing to transfer to the methions.
Not to mention the lack of funds in favor of traders: the previous debt of the state is approximately 10 million euros.
It is shameful from an ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To sustain the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year.”
Interesting the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that worried about the closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to promote and protect the cinema mono sala be in the historical center that in the periphery.
Among the rules envisaged there are mediated tax facilitation in favor of managers and advantages for the public in mobility endpoints: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for parking.
"It is an initiative that I like," notes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is true, that to contrast the extra power of meth, traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because the audience today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that was always important to me: the closure of the cinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make the "New Cinema Paradiso", which I was already thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale already closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, not to see the posters blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side.
Link between politician and 'ndrangheta, has been arrested the mayor of Gioia Tauro
